tickets.description:
Variable names inside of double quotes in print or printf statements are not being colored correctly.  

For example, in the following print statement:

print OUTPUT "Occurrence limiter set to $limiter.\n";

The variable name $limiter appears in the same color as the words 'Occurrence limiter set to'.  Ideally, $limiter should be the same color as it would be in a variable declaration.

This behavior also exhibits itself in die statements such as the following, and most likely anywhere a variable name is surrounded by double quotes:

open\( OUTPUT, "&gt;$report" \) || die "Cannot open $report: $\!";

If two data is combined with one with a "pack" function and it divides into two data with a "unpack" function, the divided data will not be normally displayed by Eclipse Console. 
When perl is started in a terminal, the divided data is displayed normally. 
This probram can be checked by the following programs.

\#----------------------------------------
\#\!/usr/bin/perl

use strict;
use warnings;

my $data = 2008;
my $str = "abcde";
my $buf\_data;
my $buf\_str;
my $rec;

print "$str : $data\n";

$rec = pack "a12 l", $str ,$data;
\($buf\_str, $buf\_data\) = unpack "a12 l", $rec;

print "$buf\_str\n";		\# good
print "$buf\_data\n";		\# good
print "$buf\_str : $buf\_data\n";	\# bad
\#----------------------------------------

