This is because the lexer thinks the s\_ is the start of a search/replace regex and that the "\_" is the delimiter. It looks for two more "\_" chars to complete the regex before normal highlighting continues. 

Consider:

my $foo = 1;

s\_foo\(\);

print "here\n";
s\_foo\(\);

sub s\_foo
\{
print "here\n";
\}

Everything between the first s\_foo\(\) and sub s\_foo should be incorrectly highlighted, but the 
\{
print "here\n";
\}

should be correct.

The same behaviour occurs for tr\_ and y\_

I'm not familiar enough with the perl.g lexer file to figure out how to fix this.

\- Jim

